descriptive_long.solution:
In all solutions, we assume that the function $boundedfunc$ is integrable.

\textbf{First solution:}
Let $stepfunc(variablex)$ be $1$ for $1\leq variablex\leq 2$ and $-1$ for $2<variablex\leq 3$, and define $diffhelper(variablex)=stepfunc(variablex)-boundedfunc(variablex)$. Then $\int_1^3 diffhelper(variablex)\,dvariablex = 0$ and $diffhelper(variablex) \geq 0$ for $1\leq variablex\leq 2$, $diffhelper(variablex) \leq 0$ for $2<variablex\leq 3$. Now
\begin{align*}
\int_1^3 \frac{diffhelper(variablex)}{variablex}\,dvariablex & = \int_1^2 \frac{|diffhelper(variablex)|}{variablex}\,dvariablex - \int_2^3 \frac{|diffhelper(variablex)|}{variablex}\,dvariablex\\
&\geq \int_1^2 \frac{|diffhelper(variablex)|}{2}\,dvariablex - \int_2^3 \frac{|diffhelper(variablex)|}{2}\,dvariablex = 0,
\end{align*}
and thus $\int_1^3 \frac{boundedfunc(variablex)}{variablex}\,dvariablex \leq \int_1^3 \frac{stepfunc(variablex)}{variablex}\,dvariablex = 2\log 2-\log 3 = \log \frac{4}{3}$. Since $stepfunc(variablex)$ achieves the upper bound, the answer is $\log \frac{4}{3}$.

\noindent
\textbf{Reformulation:}
(by Karl Mahlburg and Karthik Adimurthi) Since $boundedfunc$ is integrable, it can be expressed in terms of the Hadamard basis
\begin{align*}
hadamardzero(variablex) &= \begin{cases} 1 & variablex \in [1,2) \\ -1 & variablex \in [2,3] \\ 0 & variablex \notin [1,3] \end{cases} \\
hadamardgen(variablex) &= hadamardgen( 2(variablex-1) + 1) + hadamardgen( 2(variablex-2) + 1).
\end{align*}
More precisely, we have $boundedfunc(variablex) = \sum_{indexvar} coeffindex hadamardgen(variablex)$ for some $coeffindex$ with $|c_0| + |c_1| + |\cdots| \leq 1$. Let $integrvalue = \int_1^3 (hadamardgen(variablex) / variablex)\,dvariablex$; it is easy to show that the $integrvalue$ are strictly decreasing in $indexvar$. Thus
\[\int_1^3 (boundedfunc(variablex) / variablex) dvariablex = c_0 g_0 + c_1 g_1 + \cdots \leq 1 \cdot g_0 = \log \frac{4}{3}.\]

\noindent
\textbf{Second solution:}
(Art of Problem Solving, user \verb+libra_gold+)
Define the function $antideriv(variablex) = \int_1^{variablex} boundedfunc(variablet)\,dvariablet$ for $1 \leq variablex \leq 3$; then $antideriv(1) = antideriv(3) = 0$ and $antideriv(variablex) \leq \min\{variablex-1,3-variablex\}$. Using integration by parts, we obtain
\begin{align*}
\int_1^3 \frac{boundedfunc(variablex)}{variablex}\,dvariablex &= \int_1^3 \frac{antideriv(variablex)}{variablex^2}\,dvariablex \\
&\leq \int_1^2 \frac{variablex-1}{variablex^2}\,dvariablex + \int_2^3 \frac{3-variablex}{variablex^2}\,dvariablex \\
&= \log \frac{4}{3}.
\end{align*}
(Some minor adjustment is needed to make this completely rigorous, e.g., approximating $boundedfunc$ uniformly by continuous functions.)
